# TWO POINTERS — TYPES (WITH REAL WORLD EXAMPLES)

## 1. Left–Right Pointers

One pointer starts at beginning, one at end.
Used when
* Array/String
* Comparing pairs
* Checking symmetry

### Real-world example

File comparison

* One pointer at start of file
* One pointer at end
* Check if file content is symmetric (palindrome)

Password validation

* Compare characters from both ends

### DSA examples

* Palindrome check
* Reverse array
* Two Sum (sorted array)

-----------------------------------------------------------------

## 2. Slow–Fast Pointers (Tortoise & Hare)

* One pointer moves **slow**
* One pointer moves **fast**

### Used when

* Detect patterns
* Remove duplicates
* Cycle detection

### Real-world example

Traffic signal monitoring

* One sensor checks every car
* Another checks every second car
* Detect abnormal loops

Attendance list cleanup

* Slow pointer writes unique names
* Fast pointer scans list

### DSA examples

* Remove duplicates
* Detect loop in linked list
* Find middle element

---------------------------------------------------------

## 3. Two Arrays Pointers (Parallel pointers)

* One pointer in each array
* Move based on comparison

### Used when

* Data is sorted
* Comparing two datasets

### Real-world example

Chat message sync

* Phone messages list
* Server messages list
* Compare timestamps and sync missing ones

Bank transaction matching

* Debit list
* Credit list
* Match same amounts

### DSA examples

* Intersection of arrays
* Merge sorted arrays

------------------------------------------------------------------

## 4. Window-Style Two Pointers

### What it means

* Two pointers define a range
* Both move forward

### Used when

* Continuous range
* Sum / average / max / min

### Real-world example

App analytics

* Users active in last 10 minutes
* Window slides with time

Network monitoring

* Data packets in last X seconds

### DSA examples

* Subarray sum
* Max sum of k elements

---------------------------------------------------------

